{"key":"post-8499194","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8499194</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I *can* spawn to straight coir, but RR (at least at one point) recommended not doing that&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Actually, I was the first person around here, or any of the boards for that matter, to recommend coir as a substrate, back in '03 or '04.&amp;nbsp; Before that, it was thought that coir was only suitable as a casing material, with 'no nutes'.&amp;nbsp; My experiments showed it to be the equal of horse manure for growing certain species of mushrooms.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;As with any substrate material, coir will benefit from the addition of gypsum.&amp;nbsp; Coffee grinds are also a great addition, but coir can and has been used by itself with great results.&amp;nbsp; Another great addition is vermiculite at around ten to twenty percent by volume.&amp;nbsp; The vermiculite provides a moisture reservoir, and it also somehow serves as a pinset enhancer.&amp;nbsp; I don't know how or why other than speculation, but bulk substrates including coir tend to pin better with a bit of verm added.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8499784</next>\n<prev>8499160</prev>\n<first>8498822</first>\n<last>8506846</last>\n<when>1212931898</when>\n<utime>06/08/08 04:31 PM</utime>\n</post>"}